nks==\n{{Portal|Biography|California|Film|Television}}\n{{Commons|John Ritter}}\n* {{iMDb name|0000615}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=162269|name=John Ritter}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* [http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/john-ritter John Ritter at Emmys.com]\n* [http://www.famously-dead.com/movies/john-ritter.html Famously Dead]\n* [http://johnritterfoundation.org/ John Ritter Foundation]\n* [http://columbiasurgery.org/news/2015/08/24/john-ritter-s-life-saving-rules \"Ritter Rules\"]\n* [http://www.johnritterresearchprogram.org/ John Ritter Research Program in Aortic and Vascular Diseases]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for John Ritter\n|list =\n{{EmmyAward ComedyLeadActor 1976-2000}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestActorTVComedy 1970-1989}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ritter, John}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male comedy actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Actor Golden Globe (television) winners]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n[[Category:Comedians from California]]\n[[Category:Contestants on American game shows]]\n[[Category:Deaths from aortic dissection]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Burbank, California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actor in a Comedy Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:USC School of Dramatic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Theatre World Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Ritter"}
{"title_page": "Ossian Sars Nature Reserve", "text_new": "{{Infobox Protected area \n| name            = Ossian Sars Nature Reserve\n| iucn_category   = Ia\n| photo           = \n| photo_width     = \n| photo_caption   = \n| map_image       = Ossian Sars Nature Reserve locator map.svg\n| location        = [[Svalbard]], [[Norway]]\n| nearest_city    = [[Ny-\u00c5lesund]]\n| coords          = {{coord|79|N|23|E|region:NO|display=inline,title}}\n| area            = {{convert|12.1|km2|abbr=on}}\n| established     = 26 September 2003\n| visitation_num  = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body  = [[Norwegian Directorate for Nature Management]]\n}}\n\n'''Ossian Sars Nature Reserve''' ({{lang-no|Ossian Sars naturreservat}}) is located at the inner-most part of [[Kongsfjorden]] on [[Spitsbergen]] in [[Svalbard]], [[Norway]]. It was created on 26 September 2003 to preserve the mountain Ossian Sarsfjellet and the surrounding vegetation, although it had been protected as a plant conservatory area in 1984<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.npolar.no/en/the-arctic/svalbard/ossian-sars.html |title=Ossian Sars nature reserve |publisher=[[Norwegian Polar Institute]] |accessdate=14 November 2016 |language=English}}</ref>The [[nature reserve]] covers 12.139 square kilometers. Hiking is permitted, but tenting is not.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dnweb12.dirnat.no/nbinnsyn/asp/faktaark.asp?iid=VV00002579 |title=Ossian Sars naturreservat |publisher=[[Norwegian Directorate for Nature Management]] |accessdate=28 March 2010 |language=Norwegian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006220709/http://dnweb12.dirnat.no/nbinnsyn/asp/faktaark.asp?iid=VV00002579 |archivedate=6 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe mountain and reserve are named after biologist [[Georg Ossian Sars]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Nature reserves in Svalbard]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:Spitsbergen]]\n\n\n{{europe-protected-area-stub}}\n{{spitsbergen-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Protected area \n| name            = Ossian Sars Nature Reserve\n| iucn_category   = Ia\n| photo           = \n| photo_width     = \n| photo_caption   = \n| map_image       = Ossian Sars Nature Reserve locator map.svg\n| location        = [[Svalbard]], [[Norway]]\n| nearest_city    = [[Ny-\u00c5lesund]]\n| coords          = {{coord|79|N|23|E|region:NO|display=inline,title}}\n| area            = {{convert|12.1|km2|abbr=on}}\n| established     = 26 September 2003\n| visitation_num  = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body  = [[Norwegian Directorate for Nature Management]]\n}}\n\n'''Ossian Sars Nature Reserve''' ({{lang-no|Ossian Sars naturreservat}}) is located at the inner-most part of [[Kongsfjorden]] on [[Spitsbergen]] in [[Svalbard]], [[Norway]]. It was created on 26 September 2003 to preserve the mountain Ossian Sarsfjellet and the surrounding vegetation, although it had been protected as a plant conservatory area in 1984<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.npolar.no/en/the-arctic/svalbard/ossian-sars.html |title=Ossian Sars nature reserve |publisher=[[Norwegian Polar Institute]] |accessdate=14 November 2016 |language=English}}</ref>The [[nature reserve]] covers {{convert|12.139|km2}}. Hiking is permitted, but tenting is not.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dnweb12.dirnat.no/nbinnsyn/asp/faktaark.asp?iid=VV00002579 |title=Ossian Sars naturreservat |publisher=[[Norwegian Directorate for Nature Management]] |accessdate=28 March 2010 |language=Norwegian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006220709/http://dnweb12.dirnat.no/nbinnsyn/asp/faktaark.asp?iid=VV00002579 |archivedate=6 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe mountain and reserve are named after biologist [[Georg Ossian Sars]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Nature reserves in Svalbard]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:Spitsbergen]]\n\n\n{{europe-protected-area-stub}}\n{{spitsbergen-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CaptainAnarchy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ossian_Sars_Nature_Reserve"}
{"title_page": "Dick Vitale", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball coach and announcer}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Dick Vitale\n| image = Dick Vitale.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Dick Vitale at the dedication of Dick Vitale Court at the [[University of Detroit Mercy]]'s [[Calihan Hall]] in 2011\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1939|6|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Passaic, New Jersey]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[Seton Hall University|Seton Hall]]\n| coach_years1 = 1963\u20131964\n| coach_team1 = [[Garfield High School (New Jersey)|Garfield HS]]\n| coach_years2 = 1964\u20131971\n| coach_team2 = [[East Rutherford High School|East Rutherford HS]]\n| coach_years3 = 1971\u20131973\n| coach_team3 = [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights men's basketball|Rutgers]] (assistant)\n| coach_years4 = 1973\u20131977\n| coach_team4 = [[Detroit Titans men's basketball|Detroit]]\n| coach_years5 = 1978\u20131979\n| coach_team5 = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| overall_record = NCAA: 79\u201329<br />NBA: 34\u201360\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n| BASKHOF_year = 2008\n| CBBASKHOF_year = 2008\n}}\n'''Richard John \"Dick\" Vitale''' ({{IPAc-en|v|a\u026a|\u02c8|t|\u00e6|l}}; born June 9, 1939), also known as \"'''Dickie V'''\", is an American [[basketball]] [[sportscaster]]. A former head coach in the college and professional ranks, he is well known as a college basketball broadcaster for [[ESPN]]. He is known for catchphrases such as \"This is awesome, baby!\" and \"diaper dandy\" (outstanding freshman player), as well as enthusiastic and colorful remarks he makes during games, and has written nine books and appeared in several movies.\n\n==Early life==\nVitale was born in [[Passaic, New Jersey]], and grew up in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]. His father, John, was a piece work clothing press operator and had a second job as a security guard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/71/Dick-Vitale.html|title=Dick Vitale Biography (1939\u2013)}}</ref> His mom, Mae, worked in a factory as a seamstress and sewed coats until she suffered a stroke.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/dickvitale/news/story?id=3566939&lpos=spotlight&lid=tab7pos1|title=Hall call is simply awesome|last=Vitale|first=Dick|date=September 6, 2008|publisher=ESPN}}</ref> In kindergarten, Vitale lost the vision in his left eye due to an accident with a pencil.\nVitale graduated from [[East Rutherford High School]], and in 1963, he graduated from [[Seton Hall University]] with a bachelor of science degree in business administration. He later earned a master's degree in education from what is now [[William Paterson University]].\n\n==Coaching==\n\n===High school coaching===\nVitale took his first job as a coach at an elementary school in [[Garfield, New Jersey]] in 1958.  Eventually he moved up to the high school level to become head coach at [[Garfield High School (New Jersey)|Garfield High School]] for one season, and then at [[East Rutherford High School]] (his [[alma mater]]), where he had a record of 131\u201347 from 1964 to 1971 and led his teams to two New Jersey state championships.<ref>Moran, Malcolm. [https://www.nytimes.com/1979/02/01/archives/dick-vitale-frustrated-but-still-trying.html \"Dick Vitale: Frustrated But Still\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', February 1, 1979. Accessed January 9, 2018. \"He won two New Jersey state championships at East Rutherford High School, and had a career record of 131\u201047.\"</ref>\n\n===College coaching===\nIn 1971, Vitale moved to [[Rutgers University]] as an assistant coach under head coach Dick Lloyd. After two seasons there, he was hired in 1973 by the [[University of Detroit Mercy|University of Detroit]] to become its head coach. Vitale took [[Detroit Titans men's basketball|Detroit]] to the 32-team NCAA tournament in [[1977 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1977]]. Vitale had a 78\u201330 record during his tenure at Detroit, which included a 21-game winning streak during the 1977 season. During that streak the Titans defeated the eventual champion [[1976\u201377 Marquette Warriors men's basketball team|Marquette]], [[UW\u2013Milwaukee Panther Arena|on the road]], in [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]]. Following the 1977 season, his fourth as Detroit head coach, Vitale was named the university's [[athletic director]].\n\n===NBA coaching===\nVitale coached the [[Detroit Pistons]] of the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] for the 1978\u201379 season, leading them to a 30\u201352 (.366) record.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pistons Coaching Records |url=http://www.nba.com/pistons/history/alltime_coaching_records.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202135250/http://www.nba.com/pistons/history/alltime_coaching_records.html |archivedate=2009-12-02 }}</ref> On November 8, 1979, Pistons owner [[Bill Davidson (businessman)|Bill Davidson]] came to Vitale's house and told him that the Pistons were making a coaching change. It was twelve games into the 1979\u201380 season, after the Pistons struggled to a 4\u20138 start. The primary reason for Vitale's downfall with the Pistons was the maneuver that brought [[Bob McAdoo]] to Detroit. [[M.L. Carr]]'s decision to sign with [[Boston Celtics|Boston]] as a free agent in 1979 spawned a transaction in which the Pistons, entitled to compensation for Carr, demanded Bob McAdoo, whom the Celtics were looking to unload due to injuries. The Pistons sent two 1980 first-round draft picks (in addition to Carr) to the Celtics in exchange for McAdoo in a combination free agent signing/trade. The Pistons would have the worst season in franchise history in 1979\u201380, and their pick would become the first overall pick in the [[1980 NBA Draft|1980 draft]]. Boston then traded the two picks to the [[Golden State Warriors|Warriors]] (who selected [[Joe Barry Carroll]] with the #1 pick and [[Rickey Brown]] with the #13 pick) in exchange for [[Robert Parish]] and the #3 pick ([[Kevin McHale (basketball)|Kevin McHale]]).\n\n==Personal life==\n\nVitale married Lorraine McGrath in 1971.  The couple have two daughters, Terri and Sherri,<ref>{{cite web |title=To honor of Dick Vitale\u2019s 80th birthday, here\u2019s eight things to know about \u2018Dickie V\u2019 |url=https://www.tampabay.com/sports/2019/06/07/to-honor-of-dick-vitales-80th-birthday-heres-eight-things-to-know-about-dickie-v/ |website=Tampa Bay Times |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref> and five grandchildren.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dick Vitale |url=https://www.facebook.com/therealdickvitale/photos/my-5-grandchildren-pose-for-pic-after-dinner-at-the-utc-mall/1831389863550746/ |website=Facebook |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n\n===College===\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start | type = | conference = | postseason = | poll = }}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name       = [[Detroit Titans men's basketball|Detroit Titans]]\n | conference = [[NCAA Division I independent schools|NCAA Division I independent]]\n | startyear  = 1973\n | endyear    = 1977\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | season       = [[1973\u201374 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1973\u201374]]\n | name         = Detroit\n | overall      = 17\u20139\n | conference   =\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | season       = [[1974\u201375 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1974\u201375]]\n | name         = Detroit\n | overall      = 17\u20139\n | conference   =\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | season       = [[1975\u201376 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1975\u201376]]\n | name         = Detroit\n | overall      = 19\u20138\n | conference   =\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | season       = [[1976\u201377 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1976\u201377]]\n | name         = [[1976\u201377 Detroit Titans men's basketball team|Detroit]]\n | overall      = 26\u20133\n | conference   =\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   = [[1977 NCAA Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Division I Sweet 16]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Detroit\n | overall    = 79\u201329 ({{winpct|79|29}})\n | confrecord = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record End \n | overall = 79\u201329 ({{winpct|79|29}})\n | legend  = no\n}}\n\n===NBA===\n{{NBA coach statistics legend}}\n{{NBA coach statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1978\u201379 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1978}}\n|82||30||52||.366|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4th in Central||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Missed Playoffs\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1979\u201380 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1979}}\n|12||4||8||.333|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|(fired)||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|'''Career'''\n| ||94||34||60||{{Winning percentage|34|60}}|| || || || ||\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Broadcasting==\nFollowing his departure as coach of the [[Detroit Pistons]], [[Scotty Connal]] gave Vitale his first TV opportunity at the then fledgling [[ESPN]] cable network. His first reaction to the job of broadcaster was \"Absolutely no way. I know nothing about TV. I want to get back to where I belong and my spirit belongs.\" He was reluctant to accept the position but his wife Lorraine told him to \"go on TV and have some fun,\" so Vitale accepted on a temporary basis until another coaching job became available. He called ESPN's first [[college basketball]] game on December 5, 1979, when [[DePaul Blue Demons men's basketball|DePaul]] defeated [[Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball|Wisconsin]] 90\u201377.<ref>{{cite web | title = Vitale's first broadcast| url = http://www.jsonline.com/sports/39534602.html}}</ref> His first play-by-play partner was Joe Boyle.\n\nVitale was not a natural at first for broadcasting. He missed his first-ever production meeting when he was walking the streets of [[Chicago]]. Also, he would talk while the producers were talking to him through his earpiece, during commercials, and while the play-by-play man was talking. Vitale himself was not sure if broadcasting would fit him. Connal, who had hired him, told him, \"You have a quality we can't teach.\" Vitale did not understand this until many people wanted his autograph at the 1983 Final Four. He credits a lot of his success to working with [[Jim Simpson (sportscaster)|Jim Simpson]] at the beginning of his career.\n\nIn 1985, after the [[American Broadcasting Company]] acquired ESPN, Vitale also began doing broadcasts on the ABC network.\n\nIn 1999, Vitale was featured in a series of thirty-second promo shorts for \"Hoops Malone\".  The shorts, which aired in heavy rotation on ESPN, were presented as a sitcom featuring Vitale, [[George Gervin]] and others, including a puppet called \"O'Hoolix\".  ESPN promoted \"Hoops\" with banners and other marketing premiums, with the idea of generating buzz about the show, but no actual episodes were ever produced.  Though this led to an offer for Vitale to do an actual sitcom, he turned down the opportunity.\n\nIn December 2002, Vitale called a [[St. Vincent - St. Mary High School|St. Vincent \u2013 St. Mary's]]\u2013[[Oak Hill Academy (Virginia)|Oak Hill Academy]] prep game, featuring then high school phenom [[LeBron James]]. He announced the game with [[Brad Nessler]] and NBA great [[Bill Walton]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://usatoday.com/sports/columnist/martzke/2002-12-04-martzke_x.htm | work=USA Today | title=Packer vexed at Vitale for doing prep star's game | date=December 4, 2002 | accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy the 2004\u201305 season, Vitale was doing approximately 40 games a year.<ref>{{cite web| title=TV/RADIO: Hoops boosts Vitale's vitality| url=http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/031205/spo_18198829.shtml| access-date=2009-03-09| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706091318/http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/031205/spo_18198829.shtml#| archive-date=2015-07-06| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nVitale is signed with ESPN through the 2021\u201322 college basketball season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dick Vitale agrees to contract extension with ESPN|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/13044327/dick-vitale-agrees-contract-extension-espn|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=9 June 2015|date=2015-06-09}}</ref> Vitale was recruited to do color in the first two rounds of the NCAA tournament by [[College Basketball on CBS|CBS]] but ESPN would not allow it. However, ESPN's analysts [[Jay Bilas]] and [[Len Elmore]] were allowed to provide color for CBS's tournament coverage, teaming with play-by-play announcers [[Dick Enberg]] and [[Gus Johnson (sportscaster)|Gus Johnson]]. However, this is slightly misleading as Elmore continues to call games for both CBS and ESPN during the college basketball season; in Bilas' case he was loaned to CBS for the tournament only in 2003 and from 2005\u20132010.\n\nIn February 2015, ESPN removed Vitale from covering [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]]-[[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|UNC]] basketball. He had covered every Duke-UNC game televised by ESPN since 1979.<ref> http://www.diehardsport.com/college-basketball/espn-taken-dick-vitale-off-broadcast-unc-duke-game/</ref>\n\nVitale is a voter on the [[Associated Press|AP]] Top 25 men's basketball polls, the annual [[Naismith College Player of the Year|Naismith Award]] and the [[John Wooden Award]].\n\nVitale called his first NBA game on television since the 1984 NBA playoffs, along with [[Dan Shulman]], on January 7, 2009 when the Miami Heat played the Denver Nuggets as ESPN swapped its NBA and NCAA crews. During ESPN's first incarnation covering the NBA, he regularly covered games.\n\n===Broadcasting partners===\nAs of 2009, Vitale had called close to a thousand games. Vitale, a [[color commentator]], is primarily paired with play-by-play announcers [[Mike Patrick]], primarily those in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] games; and [[Dan Shulman]] for [[Saturday Primetime]] and other non-ACC games. During the postseason, he appears as an in-studio analyst with host [[Rece Davis]] and fellow analysts [[Jay Bilas]], [[Digger Phelps]], [[Hubert Davis]], and [[Bob Knight]]. Previously, he has been paired with [[Keith Jackson]], [[Roger Twibell]], and [[Brent Musburger]] for [[College Basketball on ABC|ABC]] as well as [[Jim Simpson (sportscaster)|Jim Simpson]], [[Tim Brando]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1142535/index.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121202230801/http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1142535/index.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 2, 2012 |work=CNN |title=You Said A Mouthful, Dick, Baby |date=March 19, 1990 |accessdate=May 1, 2010 }}</ref> [[Mike Tirico]], [[Dave O'Brien (sportscaster)|Dave O'Brien]], [[Sean McDonough]] and [[Brad Nessler]]. He worked in the studio with [[Bob Ley]], [[John Saunders (journalist)|John Saunders]], Tirico, and [[Chris Fowler]] as well as [[Jim Valvano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/dickvitale/news/story?id=3566939 |title=Hall call is simply Awesome |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2008-09-06 |accessdate=2013-12-27}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n\nOn September 5, 2008 Vitale was inducted into the [[Basketball Hall of Fame]] as a contributor to the sport, after falling just short of induction the previous year.\n\nIn 2011 the University of Detroit named their basketball court in his honor.\n\nOn August 18, 2012, he was inducted into the [[Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum|Little League Museum]] Hall of Excellence.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lembo |first=John |title=Dick Vitale honored by Little League hall induction |url=http://www.bradenton.com/2012/08/04/4142748/dick-vitale-honored-by-little.html |newspaper=Bradenton Herald |date=August 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805052422/http://www.bradenton.com/2012/08/04/4142748/dick-vitale-honored-by-little.html |archivedate=2012-08-05 }}</ref>\n\n2016 [[New Jersey Hall of Fame]] inductee.\n\n[[Italian American Sports Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Appearances in other media==\n===Video games===\n[[File:Awesomebabycollegehoopsboxart.jpg|thumb|Dick Vitale's \"Awesome Baby\" College Hoops' Box Art]]\nDick Vitale lent his name, voice and likeness to the 1994 [[Sega Genesis]] college basketball [[video game]], ''Dick Vitale's \"Awesome Baby\" College Hoops'' (a title developed and sold by [[Time Warner Interactive]].) and only released in the [[United States|U.S]] and [[Australia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://segaretro.org/Dick_Vitale%27s_%22Awesome,_Baby!%22_College_Hoops|title=Dick Vitale's \"Awesome, Baby!\" College Hoops - Sega Retro|website=segaretro.org|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref> Later, Vitale and [[Brad Nessler]] provided the commentator voices for [[EA Sports]]' [[NCAA Basketball series|NCAA Basketball]] (formerly NCAA March Madness) [[video game]] series until its 2010 discontinuation.\n===Books===\nIn 2004, Vitale released a descriptive [[autobiography]] co-written with Dick Weiss, entitled ''Living a Dream''. The book has several thoughts and comments on his days with the Pistons and ESPN, and memories of former NC State basketball Coach [[Jim Valvano]].\n\n===Product endorsements===\nVitale has appeared in commercials for [[DiGiorno]] pizza, [[Oberto Sausage Company|Oberto]] beef jerky, the [[Airborne Athletics]] basketball training device Dr. Dish, and [[Hooters]] restaurants.\n\n===Films and television===\nIn 1988, Vitale had a cameo appearance as a baseball color commentator, sharing the crowded broadcast booth with [[Curt Gowdy]], [[Jim Palmer]], [[Dick Enberg]], [[Mel Allen]], [[Tim McCarver]] and [[Joyce Brothers]] in ''[[The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!]]''. He guest starred on ''[[The Cosby Show]]'' along with friend [[Jim Valvano]] as furniture movers in the eighth-season episode ''[[List of The Cosby Show episodes#Season 8: 1991\u20131992|The Getaway]]''. Other film appearances have generally been Vitale playing himself and commentating the fictional games occurring in those films.\n\n====Film roles====\n*''[[The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!]]'' (1988) \u2013 Baseball Announcer #1\n*''[[Blue Chips]]'' (1994) \u2013 Himself\n*''[[Jury Duty (film)|Jury Duty]]'' (1995) \u2013 Hal Gibson\n*''[[The Sixth Man]]'' (1997) \u2013 Himself\n*''[[He Got Game]]'' (1998) \u2013 Himself\n*''[[Love & Basketball]]'' (2000) \u2013 Himself\n*''Complete Guide to Guys'' (2005) \u2013 Himself\n*''[[Home of the Giants]]'' (2007) \u2013 Himself\n\n==Author==\nVitale has authored nine books:\n*\"Dickie V's ABCs and 1-2-3s\", Ascend Books (October 2010)\n*\"Living a Dream: Reflections on 25 Years Sitting in the Best Seat\", Champaign, IL Sports Publishing LLC (January 1, 2003)\n*\"Dick Vitale's Fabulous 50 Players and Moments in College Basketball: From the Best Seat in the House During My 30 Years at ESPN\", Ascend Books (October 6, 2008)\n*\"Time Out Baby!\", Berkley (December 1, 1992)\n*\"Vitale\", Simon and Schuster; 1st Edition (1988)\n*\"Dickie V's Top 40 All-Everything Teams\", Masters Press (June 1994)\n*\"Tourney Time: It's Awesome Baby!\", Masters Press, (December 1993)\n*\"Holding Court: Reflections on the Game I Love\", Masters Press (November 1995)\n*\"Campus Chaos: Why the Game I Love is Breaking My Heart\", Sideline Sports Publishing (December 1999)\n*\"Getting a W in the Game of Life: Using my T.E.A.M. Model to Motivate, Elevate, and Be Great\" (Oct. 2012)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dickvitaleonline.com/ Dick Vitale Online]\n* [http://espn.go.com/dickvitale/vfile/ Vitale's \"V-File\" at ESPN.com]\n* {{Basketballhof|dick-vitale|Dick Vitale}}\n{{Navboxes| list1 =\n{{Detroit Titans men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Detroit Titans athletic director navbox}}\n{{Detroit Pistons coach navbox}}\n{{ESPN}}\n{{College Gameday (basketball)}}\n{{NBA on ABC}}\n{{Curt Gowdy Media Award}}\n{{2008 Basketball HOF}}\n{{Basketball Hall of Fame contributors}}\n{{Sports Lifetime Achievement Award}}\n{{NCAA Gerald R. Ford Award}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vitale, Dick}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:College basketball announcers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Detroit Pistons head coaches]]\n[[Category:Detroit Mercy Titans athletic directors]]\n[[Category:Detroit Mercy Titans men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:High school basketball coaches in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Indiana Pacers broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:National Collegiate Basketball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:People from East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Elmwood Park, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Rutgers Scarlet Knights men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Seton Hall University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Passaic, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:William Paterson University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American basketball coach and announcer}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Dick Vitale\n| image = Dick Vitale.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Dick Vitale at the dedication of Dick Vitale Court at the [[University of Detroit Mercy]]'s [[Calihan Hall]] in 2011\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1939|6|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Passaic, New Jersey]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[Seton Hall University|Seton Hall]]\n| coach_years1 = 1963\u20131964\n| coach_team1 = [[Garfield High School (New Jersey)|Garfield HS]]\n| coach_years2 = 1964\u20131971\n| coach_team2 = [[East Rutherford High School|East Rutherford HS]]\n| coach_years3 = 1971\u20131973\n| coach_team3 = [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights men's basketball|Rutgers]] (assistant)\n| coach_years4 = 1973\u20131977\n| coach_team4 = [[Detroit Titans men's basketball|Detroit]]\n| coach_years5 = 1978\u20131979\n| coach_team5 = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| overall_record = NCAA: 79\u201329<br />NBA: 34\u201360\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n| BASKHOF_year = 2008\n| CBBASKHOF_year = 2008\n}}\n'''Richard John \"Dick\" Vitale''' ({{IPAc-en|v|a\u026a|\u02c8|t|\u00e6|l}}; born June 9, 1939), also known as \"'''Dickie V'''\", is an American [[basketball]] [[sportscaster]]. A former head coach in the college and professional ranks, he is well known as a college basketball broadcaster for [[ESPN]]. He is known for catchphrases such as \"This is awesome, baby!\" and \"diaper dandy\" (outstanding freshman player), as well as enthusiastic and colorful remarks he makes during games, and has written nine books and appeared in several movies.\n\n==Early life==\nVitale was born in [[Passaic, New Jersey]], and grew up in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]. His father, John, was a piece work clothing press operator and had a second job as a security guard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/71/Dick-Vitale.html|title=Dick Vitale Biography (1939\u2013)}}</ref> His mom, Mae, worked in a factory as a seamstress and sewed coats until she suffered a stroke.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/dickvitale/news/story?id=3566939&lpos=spotlight&lid=tab7pos1|title=Hall call is simply awesome|last=Vitale|first=Dick|date=September 6, 2008|publisher=ESPN}}</ref> In kindergarten, Vitale lost the vision in his left eye due to an accident with a pencil.\nVitale graduated from [[East Rutherford High School]], and in 1963, he graduated from [[Seton Hall University]] with a bachelor of science degree in business administration. He later earned a master's degree in education from what is now [[William Paterson University]].\n\n==Coaching==\n\n===High school coaching===\nVitale took his first job as a coach at an elementary school in [[Garfield, New Jersey]] in 1958.  Eventually he moved up to the high school level to become head coach at [[Garfield High School (New Jersey)|Garfield High School]] for one season, and then at [[East Rutherford High School]] (his [[alma mater]]), where he had a record of 131\u201347 from 1964 to 1971 and led his teams to two New Jersey state championships.<ref>Moran, Malcolm. [https://www.nytimes.com/1979/02/01/archives/dick-vitale-frustrated-but-still-trying.html \"Dick Vitale: Frustrated But Still\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', February 1, 1979. Accessed January 9, 2018. \"He won two New Jersey state championships at East Rutherford High School, and had a career record of 131\u201047.\"</ref>\n\n===College coaching===\nIn 1971, Vitale moved to [[Rutgers University]] as an assistant coach under head coach Dick Lloyd. After two seasons there, he was hired in 1973 by the [[University of Detroit Mercy|University of Detroit]] to become its head coach. Vitale took [[Detroit Titans men's basketball|Detroit]] to the 32-team NCAA tournament in [[1977 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1977]]. Vitale had a 78\u201330 record during his tenure at Detroit, which included a 21-game winning streak during the 1977 season. During that streak the Titans defeated the eventual champion [[1976\u201377 Marquette Warriors men's basketball team|Marquette]], [[UW\u2013Milwaukee Panther Arena|on the road]], in [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]]. Following the 1977 season, his fourth as Detroit head coach, Vitale was named the university's [[athletic director]].\n\n===NBA coaching===\nVitale coached the [[Detroit Pistons]] of the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] for the 1978\u201379 season, leading them to a 30\u201352 (.366) record.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pistons Coaching Records |url=http://www.nba.com/pistons/history/alltime_coaching_records.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202135250/http://www.nba.com/pistons/history/alltime_coaching_records.html |archivedate=2009-12-02 }}</ref> On November 8, 1979, Pistons owner [[Bill Davidson (businessman)|Bill Davidson]] came to Vitale's house and told him that the Pistons were making a coaching change. It was twelve games into the 1979\u201380 season, after the Pistons struggled to a 4\u20138 start. The primary reason for Vitale's downfall with the Pistons was the maneuver that brought [[Bob McAdoo]] to Detroit. [[M.L. Carr]]'s decision to sign with [[Boston Celtics|Boston]] as a free agent in 1979 spawned a transaction in which the Pistons, entitled to compensation for Carr, demanded Bob McAdoo, whom the Celtics were looking to unload due to injuries. The Pistons sent two 1980 first-round draft picks (in addition to Carr) to the Celtics in exchange for McAdoo in a combination free agent signing/trade. The Pistons would have the worst season in franchise history in 1979\u201380, and their pick would become the first overall pick in the [[1980 NBA Draft|1980 draft]]. Boston then traded the two picks to the [[Golden State Warriors|Warriors]] (who selected [[Joe Barry Carroll]] with the #1 pick and [[Rickey Brown]] with the #13 pick) in exchange for [[Robert Parish]] and the #3 pick ([[Kevin McHale (basketball)|Kevin McHale]]).\n\n==Personal life==\n\nVitale married Lorraine McGrath in 1971.  The couple have two daughters, Terri and Sherri,<ref>{{cite web |title=To honor of Dick Vitale\u2019s 80th birthday, here\u2019s eight things to know about \u2018Dickie V\u2019 |url=https://www.tampabay.com/sports/2019/06/07/to-honor-of-dick-vitales-80th-birthday-heres-eight-things-to-know-about-dickie-v/ |website=Tampa Bay Times |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref> and five grandchildren.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dick Vitale |url=https://www.facebook.com/therealdickvitale/photos/my-5-grandchildren-pose-for-pic-after-dinner-at-the-utc-mall/1831389863550746/ |website=Facebook |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n\n===College===\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start | type = | conference = | postseason = | poll = }}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name       = [[Detroit Titans men's basketball|Detroit Titans]]\n | conference = [[NCAA Division I independent schools|NCAA Division I independent]]\n | startyear  = 1973\n | endyear    = 1977\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | season       = [[1973\u201374 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1973\u201374]]\n | name         = Detroit\n | overall      = 17\u20139\n | conference   =\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | season       = [[1974\u201375 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1974\u201375]]\n | name         = Detroit\n | overall      = 17\u20139\n | conference   =\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | season       = [[1975\u201376 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1975\u201376]]\n | name         = Detroit\n | overall      = 19\u20138\n | conference   =\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | season       = [[1976\u201377 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1976\u201377]]\n | name         = [[1976\u201377 Detroit Titans men's basketball team|Detroit]]\n | overall      = 26\u20133\n | conference   =\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   = [[1977 NCAA Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Division I Sweet 16]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Detroit\n | overall    = 79\u201329 ({{winpct|79|29}})\n | confrecord = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record End \n | overall = 79\u201329 ({{winpct|79|29}})\n | legend  = no\n}}\n\n===NBA===\n{{NBA coach statistics legend}}\n{{NBA coach statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1978\u201379 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1978}}\n|82||30||52||.366|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4th in Central||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Missed Playoffs\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1979\u201380 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1979}}\n|12||4||8||.333|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|(fired)||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014||\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|'''Career'''\n| ||94||34||60||{{Winning percentage|34|60}}|| || || || ||\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Broadcasting==\nFollowing his departure as coach of the [[Detroit Pistons]], [[Scotty Connal]] gave Vitale his first TV opportunity at the then fledgling [[ESPN]] cable network. His first reaction to the job of broadcaster was \"Absolutely no way. I know nothing about TV. I want to get back to where I belong and my spirit belongs.\" He was reluctant to accept the position but his wife Lorraine told him to \"go on TV and have some fun,\" so Vitale accepted on a temporary basis until another coaching job became available. He called ESPN's first [[college basketball]] game on December 5, 1979, when [[DePaul Blue Demons men's basketball|DePaul]] defeated [[Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball|Wisconsin]] 90\u201377.<ref>{{cite web | title = Vitale's first broadcast| url = http://www.jsonline.com/sports/39534602.html}}</ref> His first play-by-play partner was Joe Boyle.\n\nVitale was not a natural at first for broadcasting. He missed his first-ever production meeting when he was walking the streets of [[Chicago]]. Also, he would talk while the producers were talking to him through his earpiece, during commercials, and while the play-by-play man was talking. Vitale himself was not sure if broadcasting would fit him. Connal, who had hired him, told him, \"You have a quality we can't teach.\" Vitale did not understand this until many people wanted his autograph at the 1983 Final Four. He credits a lot of his success to working with [[Jim Simpson (sportscaster)|Jim Simpson]] at the beginning of his career.\n\nIn 1985, after the [[American Broadcasting Company]] acquired ESPN, Vitale also began doing broadcasts on the ABC network.\n\nIn 1999, Vitale was featured in a series of thirty-second promo shorts for \"Hoops Malone\".  The shorts, which aired in heavy rotation on ESPN, were presented as a sitcom featuring Vitale, [[George Gervin]] and others, including a puppet called \"O'Hoolix\".  ESPN promoted \"Hoops\" with banners and other marketing premiums, with the idea of generating buzz about the show, but no actual episodes were ever produced.  Though this led to an offer for Vitale to do an actual sitcom, he turned down the opportunity.\n\nIn December 2002, Vitale called a [[St. Vincent - St. Mary High School|St. Vincent \u2013 St. Mary's]]\u2013[[Oak Hill Academy (Virginia)|Oak Hill Academy]] prep game, featuring then high school phenom [[LeBron James]]. He announced the game with [[Brad Nessler]] and NBA great [[Bill Walton]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://usatoday.com/sports/columnist/martzke/2002-12-04-martzke_x.htm | work=USA Today | title=Packer vexed at Vitale for doing prep star's game | date=December 4, 2002 | accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy the 2004\u201305 season, Vitale was doing approximately 40 games a year.<ref>{{cite web| title=TV/RADIO: Hoops boosts Vitale's vitality| url=http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/031205/spo_18198829.shtml| access-date=2009-03-09| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706091318/http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/031205/spo_18198829.shtml#| archive-date=2015-07-06| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nVitale is signed with ESPN through the 2021\u201322 college basketball season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dick Vitale agrees to contract extension with ESPN|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/13044327/dick-vitale-agrees-contract-extension-espn|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=9 June 2015|date=2015-06-09}}</ref> Vitale was recruited to do color in the first two rounds of the NCAA tournament by [[College Basketball on CBS|CBS]] but ESPN would not allow it. However, ESPN's analysts [[Jay Bilas]] and [[Len Elmore]] were allowed to provide color for CBS's tournament coverage, teaming with play-by-play announcers [[Dick Enberg]] and [[Gus Johnson (sportscaster)|Gus Johnson]]. However, this is slightly misleading as Elmore continues to call games for both CBS and ESPN during the college basketball season; in Bilas' case he was loaned to CBS for the tournament only in 2003 and from 2005\u20132010.\n\nIn February 2015, ESPN removed Vitale from covering [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]]-[[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|UNC]] basketball. He had covered every Duke-UNC game televised by ESPN since 1979.<ref> http://www.diehardsport.com/college-basketball/espn-taken-dick-vitale-off-broadcast-unc-duke-game/</ref>\n\nVitale is a voter on the [[Associated Press|AP]] Top 25 men's basketball polls, the annual [[Naismith College Player of the Year|Naismith Award]] and the [[John Wooden Award]].\n\nVitale called his first NBA game on television since the 1984 NBA playoffs, along with [[Dan Shulman]], on January 7, 2009 when the Miami Heat played the Denver Nuggets as ESPN swapped its NBA and NCAA crews. During ESPN's first incarnation covering the NBA, he regularly covered games.\n\n===Broadcasting partners===\nAs of 2009, Vitale had called close to a thousand games. Vitale, a [[color commentator]], is primarily paired with play-by-play announcers [[Mike Patrick]], primarily those in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] games; and [[Dan Shulman]] for [[Saturday Primetime]] and other non-ACC games. During the postseason, he appears as an in-studio analyst with host [[Rece Davis]] and fellow analysts [[Jay Bilas]], [[Digger Phelps]], [[Hubert Davis]], and [[Bob Knight]]. Previously, he has been paired with [[Keith Jackson]], [[Roger Twibell]], and [[Brent Musburger]] for [[College Basketball on ABC|ABC]] as well as [[Jim Simpson (sportscaster)|Jim Simpson]], [[Tim Brando]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1142535/index.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121202230801/http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1142535/index.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 2, 2012 |work=CNN |title=You Said A Mouthful, Dick, Baby |date=March 19, 1990 |accessdate=May 1, 2010 }}</ref> [[Mike Tirico]], [[Dave O'Brien (sportscaster)|Dave O'Brien]], [[Sean McDonough]] and [[Brad Nessler]]. He worked in the studio with [[Bob Ley]], [[John Saunders (journalist)|John Saunders]], Tirico, and [[Chris Fowler]] as well as [[Jim Valvano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/dickvitale/news/story?id=3566939 |title=Hall call is simply Awesome |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2008-09-06 |accessdate=2013-12-27}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n\nOn September 5, 2008 Vitale was inducted into the [[Basketball Hall of Fame]] as a contributor to the sport, after falling just short of induction the previous year.\n\nIn 2011 the University of Detroit named their basketball court in his honor.\n\nOn August 18, 2012, he was inducted into the [[Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum|Little League Museum]] Hall of Excellence.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lembo |first=John |title=Dick Vitale honored by Little League hall induction |url=http://www.bradenton.com/2012/08/04/4142748/dick-vitale-honored-by-little.html |newspaper=Bradenton Herald |date=August 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805052422/http://www.bradenton.com/2012/08/04/4142748/dick-vitale-honored-by-little.html |archivedate=2012-08-05 }}</ref>\n\n2016 [[New Jersey Hall of Fame]] inductee.\n\n[[Italian American Sports Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Appearances in other media==\n===Video games===\n[[File:Awesomebabycollegehoopsboxart.jpg|thumb|Dick Vitale's \"Awesome Baby!\" College Hoops' Box Art]]\nDick Vitale lent his name, voice and likeness to the 1994 [[Sega Genesis]] college basketball [[video game]], ''Dick Vitale's \"Awesome Baby\" College Hoops'' (a title developed and sold by [[Time Warner Interactive]].) and only released in the [[United States|U.S]] and [[Australia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://segaretro.org/Dick_Vitale%27s_%22Awesome,_Baby!%22_College_Hoops|title=Dick Vitale's \"Awesome, Baby!\" College Hoops - Sega Retro|website=segaretro.org|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref> Later, Vitale and [[Brad Nessler]] provided the commentator voices for [[EA Sports]]' [[NCAA Basketball series|NCAA Basketball]] (formerly NCAA March Madness) [[video game]] series until its 2010 discontinuation.\n===Books===\nIn 2004, Vitale released a descriptive [[autobiography]] co-written with Dick Weiss, entitled ''Living a Dream''. The book has several thoughts and comments on his days with the Pistons and ESPN, and memories of former NC State basketball Coach [[Jim Valvano]].\n\n===Product endorsements===\nVitale has appeared in commercials for [[DiGiorno]] pizza, [[Oberto Sausage Company|Oberto]] beef jerky, the [[Airborne Athletics]] basketball training device Dr. Dish, and [[Hooters]] restaurants.\n\n===Films and television===\nIn 1988, Vitale had a cameo appearance as a baseball color commentator, sharing the crowded broadcast booth with [[Curt Gowdy]], [[Jim Palmer]], [[Dick Enberg]], [[Mel Allen]], [[Tim McCarver]] and [[Joyce Brothers]] in ''[[The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!]]''. He guest starred on ''[[The Cosby Show]]'' along with friend [[Jim Valvano]] as furniture movers in the eighth-season episode ''[[List of The Cosby Show episodes#Season 8: 1991\u20131992|The Getaway]]''. Other film appearances have generally been Vitale playing himself and commentating the fictional games occurring in those films.\n\n====Film roles====\n*''[[The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!]]'' (1988) \u2013 Baseball Announcer #1\n*''[[Blue Chips]]'' (1994) \u2013 Himself\n*''[[Jury Duty (film)|Jury Duty]]'' (1995) \u2013 Hal Gibson\n*''[[The Sixth Man]]'' (1997) \u2013 Himself\n*''[[He Got Game]]'' (1998) \u2013 Himself\n*''[[Love & Basketball]]'' (2000) \u2013 Himself\n*''Complete Guide to Guys'' (2005) \u2013 Himself\n*''[[Home of the Giants]]'' (2007) \u2013 Himself\n\n==Author==\nVitale has authored nine books:\n*\"Dickie V's ABCs and 1-2-3s\", Ascend Books (October 2010)\n*\"Living a Dream: Reflections on 25 Years Sitting in the Best Seat\", Champaign, IL Sports Publishing LLC (January 1, 2003)\n*\"Dick Vitale's Fabulous 50 Players and Moments in College Basketball: From the Best Seat in the House During My 30 Years at ESPN\", Ascend Books (October 6, 2008)\n*\"Time Out Baby!\", Berkley (December 1, 1992)\n*\"Vitale\", Simon and Schuster; 1st Edition (1988)\n*\"Dickie V's Top 40 All-Everything Teams\", Masters Press (June 1994)\n*\"Tourney Time: It's Awesome Baby!\", Masters Press, (December 1993)\n*\"Holding Court: Reflections on the Game I Love\", Masters Press (November 1995)\n*\"Campus Chaos: Why the Game I Love is Breaking My Heart\", Sideline Sports Publishing (December 1999)\n*\"Getting a W in the Game of Life: Using my T.E.A.M. Model to Motivate, Elevate, and Be Great\" (Oct. 2012)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dickvitaleonline.com/ Dick Vitale Online]\n* [http://espn.go.com/dickvitale/vfile/ Vitale's \"V-File\" at ESPN.com]\n* {{Basketballhof|dick-vitale|Dick Vitale}}\n{{Navboxes| list1 =\n{{Detroit Titans men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Detroit Titans athletic director navbox}}\n{{Detroit Pistons coach navbox}}\n{{ESPN}}\n{{College Gameday (basketball)}}\n{{NBA on ABC}}\n{{Curt Gowdy Media Award}}\n{{2008 Basketball HOF}}\n{{Ba